⚠️ Consequences of training past 90 degrees. Before going any further I want to say these are devastating injuries & we need to make sure our thoughts & prayers go out to these folks. There are also thousands of similar scenarios out there. While these muscle tears (pecs, quads, lats, biceps etc.) represent some of the most extreme repercussions of going past 90 deg & training heavy with full range of motion, the less obvious consequences of strength training heavy past 90 deg (with full ROM) include joint pain, chronic musculoskeletal inflammation, pulls, tears, tendinitis, strains, misalignment, imbalances, muscle spasms, muscle tightness, & more. However, these are often warning signs of more dire consequences that can occur if you continue pushing deep range of motion. So rather than sluffing these warning signs off, realize these same tears can happen to you. The only significant way to prevent these horrific injuries is to train to 90 deg. Many of these reps were “proper form” according to fitness industry standards. It’s interesting to note that these injuries often occur in highly trained individuals who have been training heavy & intensely for years. Therefore, TISSUE ADAPTATION was NOT the issue. Additionally many of these injuries were not PR’s & in fact some were calisthenics. Most of these involved slow controlled negatives not sloppy form or excessive momentum. Many of these individuals who were interviewed after the injuries said they never felt like they were unable to control the weight or the weight was too heavy. In fact some said it felt light & they thought they would easily crush the weight no problem. Many of these were done with weights these folks have done before or with loads they were capable of doing multiple reps with. Therefore LOAD MANAGEMENT was NOT the issue. Now that we’ve ruled out, “tissue adaptation” & “load management” as issues as they clearly were NOT, how do we prevent such catastrophic muscle ruptures in the future especially since most of these injuries occur when the lifter over-stretches the muscles with heavy loads? Train to 90 Deg Joint Angles period! #squat #squats #powerlifting #gym #fitspo

⚡️FOR THUNDER THIGHS⚡️ Here’s how you can train hamstrings intelligently 1️⃣ Typically, I’ll train them 2 days per week. Day 1 is a lying leg curl + a stiff leg deadlift variation. Day 2 is often only a seated curl (this is because it’s on my more quad focused leg day) 2️⃣ Everything is usually for 2-4 sets in the 6-12 rep range with at least 3 minutes of rest between each set 3️⃣ If I’m doing both a leg curl and a SLDL variation in the same workout, I’ll usually start with the leg curl. In which case, it’ll be a lying leg curl (Lying leg curls will train the hamstrings in their short position & SLDL’s will train them in their lengthened position. This leaves seated leg curls to be done on my 2nd day as the stand-alone hamstring exercise.) I really hope this helps give you some sort of direction in your training.
